sample_description: Protocols: Per plant: harvest of fine roots (< 2mm diameter) in the field, froozen in liquid nitrogen and transport to the lab on dry ice. Storage at -80°C until RNA extraction environmental samples Total RNA was extracted using the protocol of Chang S, Puryear J, Cairney J (1993, A simple and efficient method for isolating RNA from pine trees. Plant Mol Biol Rep 11:113–116). The RNA of four samples was pooled. The cDNA libraries were prepared using NEBNext Ultra RNA Library Prep Kit for Illumina (New England BioLabs, Frankfurt am Main, Germany) according to the manufactorer´s protocol

sample_description: A coefficient of variation about all microarrays of one time point was calculated using Acuity 4.0 microarray informatics software [Axon Instruments]. description: SuperSAGE library for sequencing using Illumina Hiseq2000 were generated from the nitrogen fertilized samples and control of Fagus crenata. The SuperSAGE tags were mapped to the contig sequences of the RNA-seq assembly. RPM(Read Per Million mapped reads) values of each gene in the samples were calculated to quantify gene expression and assess differential expression.
study_title: SuperSAGE analysis between nitrogen fertilized samples and control in Fagus crenata
study_description: SuperSAGE library for sequencing using Illumina Hiseq2000 were generated from the nitrogen fertilized samples and control of Fagus crenata. The SuperSAGE tags were mapped to the contig sequences of the RNA-seq assembly. RPM(Read Per Million mapped reads) values of each gene in the samples were calculated to quantify gene expression and assess differential expression.

sample_description: Protocols: Roots were quickly separated from soil, washed under running tap water, rinsed with deionized water, dried with paper towel, and immediately frozen in liquid nitrogen. Young (approx. 7 to 8 years) Fagus sylvatica L. trees were collected at a natural regeneration forest with intact roots with original forest soil and litter layer. Trees were kept outdoors under ambient conditions, protected from rain but regularly watered with demineralized water (to keep soil moisture content at approx. 0.32 m³ water per m³ soil) and a shading net to simulate natural forest light conditions. Trees were randomly relocated on a weekly basis throughout the experiment to avoid confounding location or light effects. Trees were kept this way from March 7th to July 30th. In the Morning (ca. 7:00 am) of the two treatment days, 60 mL of either deionized water, 20 mM 15KNO3 solution or 20 mM 15NH4Cl solution were added to each treatment tree of the control group and the two treatment groups, respectively (120 mL total). Trees were harvested on day 3. RNA was extracted using the CTAB method of Chang et al. (1993). mRNA libraries were constructed using the NEBNext RNA Ultra II Library Prep Kit for Illumina (New England Biolabs) according to the manufacturer's protocol.

sample_description: Protocols: A 100 cm^2 area of bark was peeled of a living tree. Developing xylem was scraped from the surface underneath and directly frozen in liquid nitrogen. Mint-2 Kit for cDNA preparation (Evrogen) & cDNA normalization TRIMMER kit (Evrogen) Frozen tissue was ground under liquid nitrogen in a ball mill (Retsch, Haan, Germany). Tissue powder (500 mg) was used for RNA extraction after Chang et al. (1993) with minor modifications: the extraction buffer contained 2% b-mercaptoethanol and no spermindine. RNA was purified (RNeasy Mini Kit, Qiagen, Venlo, Netherlands). Total RNA yield and purity were determined spectrophotometrically (NanoDrop, Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, USA). RNA integrity was assessed on an Agilent 2100 Bioanalyzer (Agilent, Santa Clara, CA, USA). TruSeq RNA Library Preparation Kit (Illumina)

sample_description: Protocols: Roots were quickly separated from soil, washed under running tap water, rinsed with deionized water, dried with paper towel, and immediately frozen in liquid nitrogen. Young (approx. 7 to 8 years) Fagus sylvatica L. trees were collected at a natural regeneration forest with intact roots with original forest soil and litter layer. Trees were kept outdoors under ambient conditions, protected from rain but regularly watered with demineralized water (to keep soil moisture content at approx. 0.32 m³ water per m³ soil) and a shading net to simulate natural forest light conditions. Trees were randomly relocated on a weekly basis throughout the experiment to avoid confounding location or light effects. Trees were kept this way from March 7th to July 30th. In the Morning (ca. 7:00 am) of the two treatment days, 60 mL of either deionized water, 20 mM 15KNO3 solution or 20 mM 15NH4Cl solution were added to each treatment tree of the control group and the two treatment groups, respectively (120 mL total). Trees were harvested on day 3. RNA was extracted using the CTAB method of Chang et al. (1993). mRNA libraries were constructed using the NEBNext RNA Ultra II Library Prep Kit for Illumina (New England Biolabs) according to the manufacturer's protocol.

sample_description: Protocols: A 100 cm^2 area of bark was peeled of a living tree. Developing xylem was scraped from the surface underneath and directly frozen in liquid nitrogen. Total RNA yield and purity were determined spectrophotometrically (NanoDrop, Thermo Fisher Scientific, Waltham, MA, USA). RNA integrity was assessed on an Agilent 2100 Bioanalyzer (Agilent, Santa Clara, CA, USA). TruSeq RNA Library Preparation Kit (Illumina)

sample_description: Protocols: Roots were quickly separated from soil, washed under running tap water, rinsed with deionized water, dried with paper towel, and immediately frozen in liquid nitrogen. Young (approx. 7 to 8 years) Fagus sylvatica L. trees were collected at a natural regeneration forest with intact roots with original forest soil and litter layer. Trees were kept outdoors under ambient conditions, protected from rain but regularly watered with demineralized water (to keep soil moisture content at approx. 0.32 m³ water per m³ soil) and a shading net to simulate natural forest light conditions. Trees were randomly relocated on a weekly basis throughout the experiment to avoid confounding location or light effects. Trees were kept this way from March 7th to July 30th. In the Morning (ca. 7:00 am) of the two treatment days, 60 mL of either deionized water, 20 mM 15KNO3 solution or 20 mM 15NH4Cl solution were added to each treatment tree of the control group and the two treatment groups, respectively (120 mL total). Trees were harvested on day 3. RNA was extracted using the CTAB method of Chang et al. (1993). mRNA libraries were constructed using the NEBNext RNA Ultra II Library Prep Kit for Illumina (New England Biolabs) according to the manufacturer's protocol.

sample_description: Young seedlings (3 month) were grown in sterile water. 10 seedlings were infected with Phytophthora citricola and 10 were control plants with mock infection. The roots of the two groups were harvested after 6 days (infected plants showing symptoms) and each group's roots were pooled. Subtractive library: Driver = RNA from control roots 97% plus P. citricola RNA (liquid culture) 3% Tester = RNA from infected roots.

sample_description: Protocols: Per plant: harvest of fine roots (< 2mm diameter) in the field, froozen in liquid nitrogen and transport to the lab on dry ice. The cDNA libraries were prepared using NEBNext Ultra RNA Library Prep Kit for Illumina (New England BioLabs, Frankfurt am Main, Germany) according to the manufactorer´s protocol

sample_description: Protocols: Per plant: harvest of fine roots (< 2mm diameter) in the field, froozen in liquid nitrogen and transport to the lab on dry ice. Storage at -80°C until RNA extraction environmental samples Total RNA was extracted using the protocol of Chang S, Puryear J, Cairney J (1993, A simple and efficient method for isolating RNA from pine trees. Plant Mol Biol Rep 11:113–116). The RNA of four samples was pooled. The cDNA libraries were prepared using NEBNext Ultra RNA Library Prep Kit for Illumina (New England BioLabs, Frankfurt am Main, Germany) according to the manufactorer´s protocol

sample_description: Young seedlings (3 month) were grown in sterile water. 10 seedlings were infected with Phytophthora citricola and 10 were control plants with mock infection. The roots of the two groups were harvested after 6 days (infected plants showing symptoms) and each group's roots were pooled. Subtractive library: Driver = RNA from control roots 98.6% plus 1.4% P. citricola RNA (liquid culture) Tester = RNA from infected roots.
